Coast journalists on Wednesday protested over the increasing cases harassment, threats, assaults and deaths believed to have been engineered by state and politicians. They successfully delivered their petition to Coast regional coordinator Nelson Marwa, citing that they have not been able to operate freely in the region since 1998. "Threats, harassment and intimidation against individual journalist have turned uglier and degenerated into actual assault and even mysterious death," the petition read in part.Eastern African Journalist Association executive member Maureen Mudi called for speedy investigations over deaths of journalists."We lost Joseph Masha mysteriously, another one got his camera damaged at the court, some of us have also received threatening text messages," she said.She said Star cameraman Elkana Jacob was briefly arrested for reporting a story on unfair dismissal of some traffic officers.The petition listed and detailed assault and deaths that have mostly been experienced since 2013.They scribes are worried that should the state fail to act quickly, the situation might get out of hand as electioneering period nears.Marwa said some cases are under investigation. He said those yet to be investigated will be looked into."I assure you that these serious concerns raised will be looked into. It is our duty to protect you," Marwa said.In September, Standard reporter Joseph Masha collapsed and died at his home in Kilifi. It is suspected he was poisoned.In April last year, Behemiah Okwemba (NTV), Reuben Ogachi (Citizen TV), Tana River County information officer Ali Wario were brutally attacked by GSU at ADC Galan a ranch.In March last year, Kwale standard correspondent Tobias Chanji was kidnapped by unknown people who introduced themselves as police officers."The said officers lured him to homestead of terror suspect Hassan Suleiman Mwayuyu before they confiscated his laptop and camera," the petition said.In March 2013, the then the Star newspaper reporter Benard Wesonga was found dead in his house with blood oozing out of his mouth."Days before he died, Wesonga had told his colleagues that he had received anonymous threatening calls over two articles he had authored on importation of expired fertilizers for sale," the petition said.In January 2013, freelance journalist Paul Masese was shot eight times and killed over a story of over-age cars from Japan with high radiation levels.Late 1999, then Nation reporter Wanjoho Mwaniki fell in a bathroom in an entertainment joint and died.Scribes believe all these incidents are connected to the stories the late and those who survived wrote that were deemed not fit for those they involved. They feel danger still looms large."The trend only points to a systematic failure by both state and non state actors to ensure that the space for journalists who report on duty holder's actions and crime bent individual regarding social justice, corruption and other matters shrinking at an alarming rate," the petition said.